r\n                ", "CMLTAG", ";\r\n        ISSN:", "0366-7022", ".\r\n    \r\n            (", "Chemical Society of Japan", ")\r\n        ", "A three-dimensional (3-D) Co coordination polymer Co(BDC)(DABCO)1/2 (BDC = 1,4-benzenedicarboxylate; DABCO = 1,4-diazabicyclo[2.2.2]octane), which has a novel lantern-type structure, was synthesized and characterized by x-ray powder diffraction patterns and elemental anal.  H-adsorption characteristics were evaluated at 77 K.  The highest measured H uptake was 2.28% at 77 K and 0.1 MPa for Co(BDC)(DABCO)1/2.", " >> More from SciFinder ", "\u00ae", "https://chemport.cas.org/services/resolver?origin=ACS&resolution=options&coi=1%3ACAS%3A528%3ADC%252BD2sXhtV2gsbjO&md5=d94aceb13424a35f60add5e8ba387682", "45. ", "Maniam", ", ", "P.", "; ", "Stock", ", ", "N.", " ", "Inorg. Chem.", " ", "2011", ",  ", "50", ",  ", "5085", "\u2013 ", "5097", "[", "ACS Full Text ", "], [", "CAS", "]", "45. ", "Investigation of Porous Ni-Based Metal-Organic Frameworks Containing Paddle-Wheel Type Inorganic Building Units via High-Throughput Methods", "Maniam, Palanikumar; Stock, Norbert", "Inorganic Chemistry", "\r\n        (", "2011", "),\r\n    ", "50", "\r\n        (", "11", "),\r\n    ", "5085-5097", "CODEN:\r\n                ", "INOCAJ", ";\r\n        ISSN:", "0020-1669", ".\r\n    \r\n            (", "American Chemical Society", ")\r\n        ", "In the search of Ni based metal-org. frameworks (MOFs) contg. paddle-wheel type building units, three chem. systems Ni2+/HnL/base/solvent with HnL = H3BTC (1,3,5-benzenetricarboxylic acid), H3BTB (1,3,5-tris(4-carboxyphenyl)benzene), and H2BDC (1,4-benzenedicarboxylic acid) were studied using high-throughput (HT) methods.  In addn. to the conventional heating, for the first time HT microwave assisted synthesis of MOFs was carried out.  Six new compds. were discovered, and their fields of formation were established.  In the first system, H3BTC was employed and a comprehensive HT-screening of compositional and process parameters was conducted.  The synthesis condition for the Ni paddle-wheel unit was detd. and two compds. [Ni3(BTC)2(Me2NH)3]\u00b7(DMF)4(H2O)4 (1a) and [Ni6(BTC)2(DMF)6(HCOO)6] (1b) were discovered (Me2NH = dimethylamine, DMF = dimethylformamide).  In the second system, the use of the extended tritopic linker H3BTB and the synthesis conditions for the paddle-wheel units led to the porous MOF, [Ni3(BTB)2(2-MeIm)1.5(H2O)1.5]\u00b7(DMF)9(H2O)6.5 (2), (2-MeIm = 2-methylimidazole).  This compd. shows a selective adsorption of H2O and H2 with a strong hysteresis.  In the third system, H2BDC was used, and the base (DABCO) was incorporated as a bridging ligand into all structures.  Thus, two pillared layered porous MOFs [Ni2(BDC)2(DABCO)]\u00b7(DMF)4(H2O)1.5 (3a) and [Ni2(BDC)2(DABCO)]\u00b7(DMF)4(H2O)4 (3b) as well as a layered compd. [Ni(BDC)(DABCO)]\u00b7(DMF)1.5(H2O)2 (3c) were isolated.  The 3a and 3b polymorphs of the [Ni2(BDC)2(DABCO)] framework can be selectively synthesized.  The combination of microwave assisted heating, low overall concn., stirring of the reaction mixts., and an excess of DABCO yields a highly cryst. pure phase of 3b.  The fields of formation of all compds. were established, and scale-up was successfully performed for 1b, 2, 3a, 3b, and 3c.  All compds. were structurally characterized.  In addn. to IR, elemental and TG analyses, gas and vapor sorption expts. were carried out.", " >> More from SciFinder ", "\u00ae", "https://chemport.cas.org/services/resolver?origin=ACS&resolution=options&coi=1%3ACAS%3A528%3ADC%252BC3MXlsFyqu7w%253D&md5=0df9eeb678b23758713951e3c4a27ba6", "46. ", "Hauptvogel", ", ", "I. M.", "; ", "Biedermann", ", ", "R.", "; ", "Klein", ", ", "N.", "; ", "Senkovska", ", ", "I.", "; ", "Cadiau", ", ", "A.", "; ", "Wallacher", ", ", "D.", "; ", "Feyerherm", ", ", "R.", "; ", "Kaskel", ", ", "S.", " ", "Inorg. Chem.", " ", "2011", ",  ", "50", ",  ", "8367", "\u2013 ", "8374", "[", "ACS Full Text ", "], [", "CAS", "]", "46. ", "Flexible and Hydrophobic Zn-Based Metal-Organic Framework", "Hauptvogel, Ines Maria; Biedermann, Ralf; Klein, Nicole; Senkovska, Irena; Cadiau, Amandine; Wallacher, Dirk; Feyerherm, Ralf; Kaskel, Stefan", "Inorganic Chemistry", "\r\n        (", "2011", "),\r\n    ", "50", "\r\n        (", "17", "),\r\n    ", "8367-8374", "CODEN:\r\n                ", "INOCAJ", ";\r\n        ISSN:", "0020-1669", ".\r\n    \r\n            (", "American Chemical Society", ")\r\n        ", "A Zn-based metal-org. framework Zn2(adb)2(dabco)\u00b74.5 DMF (K) (DUT-30(Zn), DUT = Dresden University of Technol., adb = 9,10-anthracene dibenzoate, dabco = 1,4-diazabicyclo[2.2.2]octane) was synthesized using a solvothermal route.  This MOF exhibits six crystallog. guest dependent phases.  Two of them were characterized via single crystal x-ray anal.  The as-synthesized phase K crystallizes in the orthorhombic space group Fmmm, with a 9.6349(9), b 26.235(3), and c 28.821(4) \u00c5 and consists of two interpenetrated pillar-layer networks with pcu topol.  When the substance loses 0.5 DMF mols. per formula unit, a phase transition from the kinetic phase K to a thermodn. phase T occurs.  Zn2(adb)2(dabco)\u00b74 DMF (T) crystallizes in the tetragonal space group I4/mmm, with a 19.5316(8) and c 9.6779(3) \u00c5.  During the evacuation the DUT-30(Zn) undergoes again the structural transformation to A.  The activated compd. A shows the gate pressure effect in the low pressure region of nitrogen physisorption isotherm and has a BET surface area of 960 m2 g-1 and a specific pore vol. of 0.43 cm3 g-1.  Also, DUT-30(Zn) exhibits a hydrogen storage capacity of 1.12% at 1 bar, a CO2 uptake of 200 cm3 g-1 at -78\u00b0 and 0.9 bar, and a n-butane uptake of 3.0 mmol\u00b7g-1 at 20\u00b0.  The N2 adsorption process was monitored in situ via x-ray powder diffraction using synchrotron radiation.  A low temp. induced transformation of phase A to phase V could be obsd. if the compd. was cooled under vacuum 